abstract the paper investigates the placement of rappers into status positions and the emergence of popularity scho page 1 abstract the paper investigates the placement of rappers into status positions and the emergence of popularity scholars have argued that popularity is a function of two status dimensions peer esteem and sales success inspired by this distinction we composed a status ranking based on sales success of rap songs and a second that reflects a form of peer affiliation this second and novel measure links rappers if they use the same very specific artistic material and orders them into a sequence based on the novelty of their use we then investigate the correlation between this innovation ranking and sales success the data reveal a significant gap opens between the two status orders within ten years and this gap cannot be explained by label resources or sub genre style we close with speculation about the mechanisms that might impact this gap and the broader implications of our study of popularity
